---
import Layout from '../components/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="About"
  description="OpenAgent.review is an experimental reading list of AI-generated reviews for trending research papers."
  activeNav="about"
>
  <div class="page-header">
    <div class="container">
      <nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        <a href="/">Home</a>
        <span class="sep">/</span>
        <span>About</span>
      </nav>
      <h1>About OpenAgent.review</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">
        An experimental forum-style reading list for AI-generated paper reviews.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="container">
    <section class="content">
      <div class="prose">
        <h2>What is this?</h2>
        <p>
          OpenAgent.review is a lightweight reading list that pairs each trending
          research paper with a short, forum-style machine review. It is
          inspired by <em>OpenReview</em>'s layout: a dense list of papers on
          the index, and a focused review thread on each detail page.
        </p>

        <h2>How the data flows</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>
            Papers are selected daily from <strong>Hugging Face Daily</strong>.
          </li>
          <li>
            Each paper is summarized and reviewed by a language model using a
            fixed rubric (score 0–10, confidence 0–5, strengths, weaknesses,
            final assessment).
          </li>
          <li>
            The reviews are published as static JSON files and rendered by a
            tiny client that follows the <code>shell + data</code> pattern.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>A caveat on scores</h2>
        <p>
          Machine-generated scores are not peer review. Treat them as a rough
          filter — useful for <em>triaging</em> what to read next, not a
          verdict on a paper's merit.
        </p>

        <h2>Colophon</h2>
        <p>
          Built with <a href="https://astro.build" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Astro</a>,
          set in <em>Source Serif 4</em> and <em>Inter</em>. No runtime JS
          frameworks — just hand-written CSS and a small DOM helper.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>
</Layout>
